    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>New York's Reservoirs</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter by New York City Councilmen Peter Vallone and Stanley Michels criticizes delays in repairing sewage treatment plants and warns of threat to reservoirs and water supply (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Your April 27 editorial about the delays in repairing sewage treatment plants was right on the mark.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Your April 27 editorial about the delays in repairing sewage treatment plants was right on the mark.</p>
        <p>Protecting the land around the reservoirs is a vital issue in which we have been deeply involved. It was the City Council that originally brought upstate and downstate representatives together in a meeting that ultimately led to the 1997 Watershed Agreement to protect our water supply.</p>
        <p>Further delays on this repair project may jeopardize the quality of our water supply and may force the city to build a filtration plant estimated to cost up to $8 billion. If that occurred, the cost to our residents for water and sewage charges would jump sky-high. That, we cannot allow.</p>
        <p>PETER F. VALLONE  STANLEY E. MICHELS  New York, April 28, 2000</p>
        <p>The writers are, respectively, speaker of the New York City Council and chairman of the Council's Committee on Environmental Protection.</p>
      </block>
